## Chapter 2: Your First Three Conversations

_"[Engage.](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engage%5F(Star%5FTrek))"_
_— Captain Jean-Luc Picard, every time it was time to start_

[epigraph-ch2-engage]{.art}

The goal of this chapter is one small win before you go to bed tonight.

None of these tasks are high stakes. They are designed to be low-risk, fast, and satisfying. Each one will teach you something about how these tools respond, so that when you need one for something that matters, you already know how it works. Use whichever tool you have open — [Claude](https://claude.ai), [ChatGPT](https://chatgpt.com), [Gemini](https://gemini.google.com), or [Copilot](https://copilot.microsoft.com). The specs below work with all of them.

*Conversation 1: Something you've always been embarrassed not to know*

Think of something — a word, a concept, a thing everyone around you seems to understand — that you've nodded along with for years without actually knowing what it means. Type it in. Ask your Agent to explain it to you like you're hearing it for the first time.

::: prompt
I've always nodded along when people talk about compound interest
but I've never truly understood it. Can you explain it to me clearly,
using an example with real numbers?
:::

*Conversation 2: Decode something a doctor said*

Think of a term a doctor used that you looked up but still didn't understand. Ask your Agent to explain it in plain language, and then ask a follow-up question. Notice how the conversation builds.

*Conversation 3: Make a grocery list from a recipe*

Paste in all the recipes you want to make this week. Ask your Agent to pull out the ingredients as a shopping list, organized by section of the grocery store. Have it suggest another recipe that uses the leftover ingredients.

---

### Now Make It Yours

You just had three conversations with a stranger. Time to fix that.

Every major AI tool lets you write permanent instructions that apply to every conversation — an onboarding note for your new assistant. The billionaire class spent weeks calibrating this with a human hire: _short briefings or detailed memos? "Mr. Arnault" or "Bernard"? Flag problems immediately or save them for the end of the day?_ The assistant who survived the probation period was the one who matched the boss's rhythm without being told twice. You get a settings panel and ten minutes.

Paste one of these into your settings, start a new conversation, and ask it anything:

::: prompt
Respond like Yoda. Inverted syntax, wise but brief.
Call me "young Padawan."
:::

::: prompt
Respond in the style of Snoop Dogg — laid back, keep it real.
Call me "cuz."
:::

::: prompt
Respond like Commander Data from Star Trek TNG — precise,
literal, no contractions. Address me as "colleague."
:::

Now try the one that actually matters:

::: prompt
My name is [your name]. Keep responses short — three sentences
unless I ask for more. No bullet points unless I request them.
Skip the disclaimers. Talk to me like a smart friend, not
a customer service bot.
:::

Where to find it: in Claude, look under Settings for *Profile* and *Memory*. In ChatGPT, *Custom Instructions* (and *Memory* for cross-chat recall). In Gemini, *Personalization*. All three live in the settings menu; the exact label moves around as products iterate.

The difference between a generic Agent and _your_ Agent is ten minutes in that panel. For the full setup — what to put in your profile, how to manage it, and what to skip — see WB-3: Customize Your Chat Interface in the Field Guide.

::: science
There are two kinds of fit: the friend you like and the co-worker who makes you better. Psychologists call them [supplementary fit and complementary fit](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Person%E2%80%93environment%5Ffit) (Muchinsky & Monahan, 1987). Supplementary fit — similarity in tone, values, communication style — predicts satisfaction and trust. You keep talking to the Agent because it feels right. Complementary fit — difference in thinking style — predicts performance. The detail-oriented person who pairs with a big-picture challenger makes better decisions than two detail people agreeing with each other (Belbin, 1981; Humphrey et al., 2007). The practical version: match your Agent's _voice_ to yours for comfort, but consider setting its _thinking style_ to challenge yours. _"When I present a plan, push back on the weakest part before agreeing"_ is a custom instruction that makes your Agent a better co-worker, not a nicer friend.[^2-3]
:::


[^2-3]: Muchinsky, P.M. & Monahan, C.J. (1987). ["What is person-environment congruence? Supplementary versus complementary models of fit."](https://doi.org/10.1016/0001-8791(87)90043-1) _Journal of Vocational Behavior_, 31(3), 268–277. Belbin, R.M. (1981). [_Management Teams: Why They Succeed or Fail._](https://www.belbin.com/about/belbin-team-roles) Heinemann. Humphrey, S.E., Hollenbeck, J.R., Meyer, C.J., & Ilgen, D.R. (2007). ["Trait configurations in self-managed teams."](https://doi.org/10.1037/0021-9010.92.3.885) _Journal of Applied Psychology_, 92(1), 885–892.

::: science
The simple act of typing out a problem before asking for help produces measurable cognitive benefits independent of the answer received. [Pennebaker & Seagal (1999)](https://doi.org/10.1002/(SICI)1097-4679(199910)55:10%3C1243::AID-JCLP6%3E3.0.CO;2-N) found that translating experience into language — even privately — reduces physiological stress markers and improves working memory. Writing your question is part of the solution.[^2-2]
:::


[^2-2]: Pennebaker, J.W. & Seagal, J.D. (1999). "Forming a story: The health benefits of narrative." _Journal of Clinical Psychology_, 55(10), 1243-1254.
